Version Date: 2010-03-30Version Text: 2010-03-30Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Users should be aware that, while the principal investigators used hotdecking imputation for some of the missing parole and community data in their models in the 2008 "Parole Violations and Revocations in California" report (see Grattet, Petersilia, and Lin, NCJ 224521
<a href="http://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/224521.pdf">http://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/224521.pdf</a>
), both the Parole Violations Data (Part 1) and the Parole Revocations Data (Part 2) that are being distributed as part of this data collection are unimputed data since secondary users of the data may want to use an alternative imputation strategy or no imputation at all.  For details about how the imputation was completed for the final report contact the authors.;Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Users should be aware that there is a small difference in the case count reported in the original final report and the original revocations codebook versus the case count in the Parole Revocations Data (Part 2) and ICPSR codebook that are being distributed as part of this data collection.;Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: A total of 13,070 parolees were observed for a maximum of 106 weeks during 2003-2004, yielding a total of 1,376,820 parolee-week observations for the Parole Violations Data (Part 1).  Specifically, the number of parolee-week observations per parolee ranges in the Part 1 data from 9 to 106, with approximately 73 percent observed for 106 weeks, 93 percent observed for 105 or 106 weeks, and 98 percent observed for 104 to 106 weeks.; Subject: null  Type: null  Notes: Stata system file(s), sav Data file(s), stc Data file(s), tsv Data file(s), Data file(s), and electronic documentation.;
